\name{simulate_data}
\alias{simulate_data}

\title{
Simulate Longitudinal Scalar-on-Function Data
}

\description{
Generates simulated longitudinal scalar-on-function data for evaluating
longitudinal functional partial least squares (LFPLS). The function creates
longitudinal functional predictors with subject-specific functional
intercept and slope components, visit-specific functional deviations,
scalar covariates, random intercepts, and scalar responses.
}

\usage{
simulate_data(case = c("1", "2"),
              nI = 100,
              nV = 4,
              tps = seq(0.5, 99.5, by = 1),
              sigma_x = 0.05,
              sigma_y = 0.35,
              sigma_b = 0.50,
              q_scalar = 5,
              theta_true = NULL)
}

\arguments{
  \item{case}{
Character string specifying the simulation scenario. Use \code{"1"} for
the global functional-effect case and \code{"2"} for the component-specific
longitudinal functional-effect case.
}

  \item{nI}{
Number of subjects. The default is \code{100}.
}

  \item{nV}{
Nominal number of visits per subject. The function generates an unbalanced
longitudinal design with total sample size approximately \code{nI * nV}.
The default is \code{4}.
}

  \item{tps}{
Numeric vector giving the grid points of the functional domain. The default
is \code{seq(0.5, 99.5, by = 1)}.
}

  \item{sigma_x}{
Standard deviation of the additive measurement noise in the observed
functional predictor. The default is \code{0.05}.
}

  \item{sigma_y}{
Standard deviation of the scalar response error. The default is
\code{0.35}.
}

  \item{sigma_b}{
Standard deviation of the scalar subject-specific random intercept in the
response model. The default is \code{0.50}.
}

  \item{q_scalar}{
Number of scalar covariates generated for the scalar part of the response
model. If \code{q_scalar = 0}, no scalar covariates are included. The
default is \code{5}.
}

  \item{theta_true}{
Optional numeric vector of true scalar regression coefficients. If
\code{NULL}, the default value is
\code{c(0.6, -0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1)}. Its length should be compatible with
\code{q_scalar}.
}
}

\details{
The function generates data from a longitudinal scalar-on-function
simulation design motivated by the LFPLS model. For subject \eqn{i} and
visit \eqn{j}, the latent functional predictor is generated from the
longitudinal decomposition
\deqn{
X_{ij}^{latent}(s)
=
\eta(s,t_{ij}) + B_{i0}(s) + t_{ij}B_{i1}(s) + U_{ij}(s),
}
where \eqn{\eta(s,t)} is a smooth mean surface, \eqn{B_{i0}(s)} is a
subject-specific functional intercept component, \eqn{B_{i1}(s)} is a
subject-specific functional slope component, and \eqn{U_{ij}(s)} is a
visit-specific deviation component.

The functional components are generated using a weighted orthonormal basis
constructed from cubic B-spline functions, trigonometric functions, and
localized Gaussian-shaped functions over the standardized functional
domain. The coefficient vectors for the subject-specific and visit-specific
functional components are generated from multivariate normal distributions
with Toeplitz covariance structures. The observed functional predictor is
then generated by adding independent Gaussian measurement noise:
\deqn{
X_{ij}(s) = X_{ij}^{latent}(s) + e_{ij}^{X}(s).
}

The scalar response includes a scalar random intercept, optional scalar
covariate effects, and a functional regression signal. Specifically,
\code{case = "1"} corresponds to a global-effect setting in which the
response is driven by a single coefficient function acting on the full
latent functional predictor:
\deqn{
Y_{ij}
=
b_i + Z_{ij}^{\top}\theta
+
1.50 \int X_{ij}^{latent}(s)\beta(s)\,ds
+
\epsilon_{ij}.
}
This case represents a setting where a single global coefficient function
is sufficient to describe the functional regression effect.

In contrast, \code{case = "2"} corresponds to a component-specific
longitudinal setting in which the response depends separately on the
between-subject functional component and the visit-specific deviation
component:
\deqn{
Y_{ij}
=
b_i + Z_{ij}^{\top}\theta
+
1.60 \int B_{ij}^{comp}(s)\beta_B(s)\,ds
+
1.10 \int U_{ij}^{comp}(s)\beta_U(s)\,ds
+
\epsilon_{ij}.
}
This second case is designed to evaluate methods that exploit the
longitudinal decomposition of the functional predictor. It is particularly
relevant for comparing supervised LFPLS with unsupervised longitudinal
functional principal component regression and global penalized functional
regression approaches.

The function returns both the observed data and the latent quantities used
to generate them. Therefore, it is useful for simulation studies, method
comparison, debugging, and examples for \code{\link{prepare_lfpls}},
\code{\link{lfpls_iterate}}, and \code{\link{tune_lfpls}}.
}

\value{
A list containing the simulated data and truth:

  \item{case}{
Simulation case used to generate the data.
}

  \item{nI}{
Number of subjects.
}

  \item{n}{
Total number of subject-visit observations.
}

  \item{Jvec}{
Vector containing the number of visits for each subject.
}

  \item{subject}{
Subject identifier for each observation.
}

  \item{times}{
Standardized visit times for all subject-visit observations.
}

  \item{tps}{
Functional grid points.
}

  \item{X}{
Observed functional predictor matrix. Rows correspond to subject-visit
observations and columns correspond to functional grid points.
}

  \item{y}{
Simulated scalar response vector.
}

  \item{mu_true}{
Conditional mean of the scalar response before adding the response error.
}

  \item{Z}{
Matrix of generated scalar covariates. If \code{q_scalar = 0}, this is a
matrix with zero columns.
}

  \item{theta_true}{
True scalar regression coefficient vector used to generate the scalar
covariate effect.
}

  \item{W_latent}{
Latent functional predictor matrix before additive measurement noise is
added.
}

  \item{B_comp}{
Between-subject functional component used in the response-generating
mechanism.
}

  \item{U_comp}{
Visit-specific functional deviation component used in the response-
generating mechanism.
}

  \item{eta_mat}{
Smooth mean-surface component evaluated at the observed visit times and
functional grid points.
}

  \item{Psi}{
Weighted orthonormal basis used to generate the functional components.
}

  \item{truth}{
A list containing the true coefficient functions. For \code{case = "1"},
\code{truth$beta_true} contains the global coefficient function and
\code{truth$beta_B_true} and \code{truth$beta_U_true} are \code{NULL}. For
\code{case = "2"}, \code{truth$beta_B_true} and
\code{truth$beta_U_true} contain the true between-subject and within-subject
coefficient functions, while \code{truth$beta_true} is \code{NULL}.
}
}

\seealso{
\code{\link{prepare_lfpls}},
\code{\link{lfpls_iterate}},
\code{\link{tune_lfpls}}
}

\examples{
\donttest{

## Case 1: global functional coefficient setting
dat1 <- simulate_data(
  case = "1",
  sigma_x = 0.05,
  sigma_y = 0.35,
  sigma_b = 0.50
)

names(dat1)
dim(dat1$X)
length(dat1$y)
table(dat1$subject)

## True global coefficient function
plot(dat1$tps, dat1$truth$beta_true, type = "l",
     xlab = "Functional domain",
     ylab = "Coefficient",
     main = "True global coefficient function")

## Case 2: component-specific longitudinal effects
dat2 <- simulate_data(
  case = "2",
  sigma_x = 0.05,
  sigma_y = 0.35,
  sigma_b = 0.50
)

## True between-subject and within-subject coefficient functions
plot(dat2$tps, dat2$truth$beta_B_true, type = "l",
     xlab = "Functional domain",
     ylab = "Coefficient",
     ylim = range(dat2$truth$beta_B_true, dat2$truth$beta_U_true),
     main = "True between-subject coefficient")

lines(dat2$tps, dat2$truth$beta_U_true, lty = 2)

## Prepare the simulated data for LFPLS
prep <- prepare_lfpls(
  y = dat2$y,
  subject = dat2$subject,
  times = dat2$times,
  X = dat2$X,
  tps = dat2$tps,
  scalar_cov = dat2$Z,
  presmooth_X = TRUE,
  df_spline = 10,
  df_time_eta = 5,
  df_time_Z = 4,
  lme_maxiter = 80
)

fit <- tune_lfpls(
  prep = prep,
  n_comp_b0_grid = 1:5,
  n_comp_b1_grid = 1:5,
  n_comp_u_grid  = 1:5,
  lambda_b_grid  = c(1e-2, 5e-2, 1e-1),
  max_iter = 6,
  tol = 1e-4,
  ortho = TRUE,
  ridge = 1e-10,
  lme_maxiter = 80
)

names(fit)
}
}
